atic vtg mRNA", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.8801093101501465, "span": {"begin": 796, "end": 812}}, {"id": ["mesh:D020888"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "VTG", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9875681400299072, "span": {"begin": 851, "end": 854}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:246319"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "hepatic vtg mRNA", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9311239123344421, "span": {"begin": 902, "end": 918}}, {"id": ["mesh:D020888"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "VTG", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9924024343490601, "span": {"begin": 991, "end": 994}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:246319"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "vtg", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9869399070739746, "span": {"begin": 1116, "end": 1119}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:246319"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "VTG", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.826335072517395, "span": {"begin": 1180, "end": 1183}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "sheepshead minnows", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.941292405128479, "span": {"begin": 1229, "end": 1247}}, {"id": ["mesh:D004997"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "17&alpha;-ethinylestradiol", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9995238184928894, "span": {"begin": 1298, "end": 1324}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:46616"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "EE2", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9997276067733765, "span": {"begin": 1326, "end": 1329}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "fathead minnows", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9223909378051758, "span": {"begin": 1337, "end": 1352}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:246319"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "vtg mRNA", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9688535928726196, "span": {"begin": 1381, "end": 1389}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:246319"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "VTG", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9499218463897705, "span": {"begin": 1527, "end": 1530}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:246319"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "vtg mRNA", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9882920384407043, "span": {"begin": 1645, "end": 1653}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "fathead minnows", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.8643734455108643, "span": {"begin": 1706, "end": 1721}}, {"id": ["mesh:D004958"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "E2", "obj": "drug", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 1733, "end": 1735}}, {"id": ["mesh:C546883"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "FC-10 diol", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9988211393356323, "span": {"begin": 1740, "end": 1750}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:246319"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "hepatic vtg", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9563995599746704, "span": {"begin": 1778, "end": 1789}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:246319"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "VTG", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.4925369620323181, "span": {"begin": 1836, "end": 1839}}], "text": "&nbsp;    In male tilapia, 48 hours after 17&beta;-estradiol (E2) treatment, vtg hepatic mRNA expression was elevated as was plasma VTG (Davis et al., 2008).  In time course studies an increase in vtg mRNA synthesis precedes increases in plasma VTG concentration. For example, a study using male fathead minnows injected with E2, vtg mRNA was detected in the liver within 4 hours, reached a maximum around 48 hours, and returned to normal levels after 6 days.&nbsp; Plasma VTG was detectable within 16 hours of treatment, reached&nbsp; maximum levels at about 72 hours, and did not return to normal levels for at least 18 days (Korte et al., 2000).  Similar results were observed in a flow-through experiment using sheepshead minnows exposed to E2 and p-nonylphenol. A dose dependent increase in hepatic vtg mRNA initially occurred followed by plasma VTG increase. Their results further supported that hepatic vtg mRNA rapidly diminishes after termination of estrogenic exposure, but plasma VTG clearance is concentration and time dependent (Hemmer et al., 2002).  Bowman et al. (2000) also found a time lag between vtg, which was elevated after 4 hours while induction of plasma VTG wasn&rsquo;t detected until 24 hours in male sheepshead minnows injected with E2.  During waterborne exposures to 17&alpha;-ethinylestradiol (EE2), male fathead minnows showed a strong increase of vtg mRNA within 3 days (first sampling time point in the study), which remained elevated for the entirety of the 35-day exposure. Although plasma VTG was first detectable on day 3 it did not significantly increase until day 14 further illustrating the lag between vtg mRNA and plasma increase (Schmid et al., 2002).  In male fathead minnows exposed to E2 and FC-10 diol for 21 days, expression of hepatic vtg was significantly increased as was the plasma VTG (Ankley et al. in prep).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 14:35:36 +0000 2026"}